Reference-contexts: In <ref> [3] </ref>, the artificial ant has to traverse the John Muir trail placed in a grid world. The ant's task is to move from cell to cell traversing as many cells in the trail as possible in 200 time steps. <p> The results indicated that both representation types can enable an artificial ant to traverse the entire cells of the trail by collecting all the food. However, the degree of the generality of the solutions is not clear. In their paper <ref> [3] </ref> the authors explicitly state that the aim of the experiment is not to evolve "a general trail-following ability" but an ability to traverse the particular trail. <p> In fact, at the end of their experiments, this was exactly what was found: `Such efficient logic seems exquisitely adapted to the features of this particular trail, and suggest that evolution has had effect of "compiling" knowledge of this environment into structure of the organism' <ref> [3] </ref>. For example, the best ant developed an evolutionary bias towards right-turning. If this best individual is tested on several similar trails which may require more left turns or other characteristics, the performance can be expected to decrease drastically.
